'''Bimbashi Arabic''' ("soldier Arabic", or '''Mongallese''') was a [[pidgin]] of [[Arabic]] which developed among military troops in [[Anglo-Egyptian Sudan]], and was popular from 1870 to 1920 CE.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Pidginization and Creolization of Languages|publisher=CUP Archive|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wG08AAAAIAAJ|page=518|accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref> Bimbashi later branched and developed into three languages: [[Turku language|Turku]] in [[Chad]], [[Ki-Nubi]] in [[Kenya]] and [[Uganda]], and [[Juba Arabic]] in [[South Sudan]].<ref name="google2">{{cite book|title=مساهمات في اللغويات العربية|publisher=Kotobarabia.com|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pb8dH-VbqL0C|page=24|accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Varieties of Arabic]] *[[Nubi language]]
==Further reading== *{{cite book|title=Modern Arabic: Structures, Functions, and Varieties|author=Holes, C.|date=2004|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=9781589010222|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8E0Rr1xY4TQC|page=26|accessdate=2015-02-22}}
