The '''Congress of Catalan Culture''' (<span contenteditable="false">in</span> Catalan, el Congrés de Cultura Catalana, abbreviated as '''CCC''') was a group of activities organized by the School of Lawyers of Barcelona, geared towards the study and diffusion of the [[Catalan language|Catalan]] culture, developed between 1975 and 1978.<ref name="EB">{{Harvard citation|AA.VV.|2006|p=66}}</ref>

The aim was to promote the Catalan culture through diverse proposals for the future, which were concretized  in a group of twenty-three fields of study, developed by experts in diverse fields of the Catalan culture. Under the presidency of [[Jordi Rubió|Jordi Rubió i Balaguer]], a commission travelled during the course of the year 1976 throughout the entire geography of the so-called [[Països Catalans|Catalan Countries]] ([[Catalonia]], [[Valencian Community|Valencia]], [[Balearic Islands|Balearic]], [[Andorra]] and [[Roussillon|Rosellón]]), gathering information and proposals that were compiled into three volumes. In total 12,400 congressmen participated.<ref name="EB"/>

Among other actions, the congress expressed the desirability of safeguarding aspects such as natural heritage and the identification of the territory, the official use of the [[Catalan language]], the revitalization of the culture and the folklore popular, and the maintenance of the Catalan institutions.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia
 | title =Congrés de Cultura Catalana.
 | encyclopedia =L'Enciclopèdia.cat
 | volume =
 | pages =
 | publisher =Grup Enciclopèdia Catalana
 | date =
 | id =
| url= http://www.enciclopedia.cat/EC-GEC-0019341.xml
 | access-date =August 26, 2016 }}</ref>
Given the success of the initiative, to the closing of the campaign <span contenteditable="false">in</span> December 1978 accorded the establishment of a foundation in charge of the maintenance and consolidation of the Catalan culture, called Foundation Congress of Catalan Culture (in Catalan, Fundació Congrés of [[Catalan language|Catalan]] Culture), sponsored by the School of Lawyers of Barcelona, Acció Cultural of the Country Valencià and Balearic Cultural Work, in addition to diverse elective employers.<ref name="EB"/>

