[[File:Police pick-up truck in Cambodia.jpg|thumb|Cambodian police car in [[Phnom Penh]]]] '''Crime''' is present in various forms in [[Cambodia]].
== Crime by type ==
===Murder=== {{Further|List of countries by intentional homicide rate}}
In 2012, Cambodia had a murder rate of 6.5 per 100,000 population.<ref name=UNODC/> There were a total of 964 murders in Cambodia in 2012.<ref name=UNODC>[https://www.unodc.org/gsh/en/index.html ''Global Study on Homicide''. [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]], 2013.]</ref>
=== Robbery === Petty crime is common, with tourist areas often targeted. This includes [[snatch theft]] and pick-pocketing. Perpetrators are usually stricken with poverty, and as a result are driven to steal from foreigners with the knowledge that they bring about a significant amount of money and other valuable items. Owing to the easy accessibility of arms, armed robbery also occurs.<ref name="travel.state.gov">{{cite web |url=https://travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/cis/cis_1080.html |publisher=travel.state.gov |title=Cambodia |accessdate=June 13, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620151830/http://travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/cis/cis_1080.html |archivedate=June 20, 2013 |df= }}</ref>
===Corruption === {{Further|Corruption in Cambodia}}
The rate of corruption in Cambodia is high; one source goes on to describe the situation as "nothing less than obscene". Corruption is considered a large expense to the Cambodian government.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CtXYNtLJYOoC&pg=PA147 |pages=147– |title=Cambodia Reborn?: The Transition to Democracy and Development |last=Curtis |first=Grant |year=1998 |publisher=Brookings Institution Press |isbn=9780815791379 }}</ref> The Cambodian police force is known to inappropriately use violence in certain cases.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wbru.com/2013/01/protest-claims-police-brutality-in-cambodian-home-drug-arrest/ |publisher=95.5 WBRU |title=Protest Claims Police Brutality in Cambodian Home |date=January 14, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212235029/http://www.wbru.com/2013/01/protest-claims-police-brutality-in-cambodian-home-drug-arrest |archivedate=December 12, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The misuse of ferocity has raised concerns from the Human Rights Watch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2013/02/01/cambodia-escalating-violence-misuse-courts |date=February 1, 2013 |title=Cambodia: Escalating Violence, Misuse of Courts |publisher=Human Rights Watch }}</ref>
===Prostitution=== {{main|Prostitution in Cambodia}}
[[Prostitution]] is against the law [[Prostitution in Cambodia|in Cambodia]], but still present and only growing. Le Thi Quy, a professor from the Women's Research Center, interviewed a handful of females in 1993 about prostitution; three quarters of the interviewees found being a prostitute to be a [[norm (social)|norm]] and a profession they felt was not shameful having.<ref name="Barry 1"/> That same year, the professor estimated that there were some one hundred thousand sex workers in the country.<ref name="Barry 1">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p8N-zQGWVf8C&pg=PA137 |pages=137– |title=The Prostitution of Sexuality |first=Kathleen |last=Barry |publisher=NYU Press |year=1996 |isbn=9780814712771 }}</ref>
== See also == * [[Drugs in Cambodia]]
