{{for|the basketball player|Jack Gibbs (basketball)}} {{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Jack P. Gibbs | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|08|26}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | pronounce = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = American | fields = [[Sociology]], [[criminology]] | workplaces = [[Vanderbilt University]], [[University of Texas at Austin]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Oregon]] (Ph.D., 1957) | thesis_title = A sociological study of suicide | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = 1957 | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = [[Social control theory]], [[deterrence (penology)|deterrence]] | influences = | influenced = | awards = [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] in sociology (1972),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/jack-porter-gibbs/ |title=Jack Porter Gibbs |website=www.gf.org |language=en-US |access-date=2017-08-26}}</ref> [[Fulbright Scholarship]]<ref name=deviance>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CUhWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA164 |title=The Sociology of Deviance: 2nd Ed |last=Franzese |first=Robert J. |date=2015-08-11 |publisher=Charles C Thomas Publisher |isbn=9780398090807 |pages=164 |language=en}}</ref> | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Jack Porter Gibbs''' (born August 26, 1927)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n80132067.html |title=Jack P. Gibbs |website=id.loc.gov |access-date=2017-08-26}}</ref> is an American sociologist known for his work on [[social control theory]] and [[deterrence (penology)|deterrence]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Why Spree Killers Kill Themselves |url=https://www.wired.com/2012/12/why-spree-killers-kill-themselves/ |magazine=WIRED |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Tullock |first=Gordon |date=Summer 1974 |title=Does Punishment Deter Crime? |url=https://www.nationalaffairs.com/public_interest/detail/does-punishment-deter-crime |magazine=National Affairs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1985/1114/ajust.html |title=Certainty of punishment may deter spies more than stiff sentences |last=Richey |first=Warren |date=1985-11-14 |work=Christian Science Monitor |access-date=2017-08-26 |issn=0882-7729}}</ref> In the early 1960s, he and [[Leonard Broom]] helped plan the founding of the Population Research Center at the [[University of Texas at Austin]], which was founded in 1963.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://liberalarts.utexas.edu/sociology/_files/pdfs/history_glenn.pdf |title=History of the University of Texas at Austin Sociology Department}}</ref> A 2015 book described Gibbs as "a giant of his time".<ref name=deviance/>
