{{Orphan|date=January 2018}}
'''Jessica Govea Thorbourne''' (1947 - January 23, 2005) was a labor activist, [[United Farm Workers|United Farm Worker]] union leader, and educator. She is best known for her lifelong efforts to achieve justice, equality, education, and economic opportunity for Latino laborers.<ref name=":7" /> At age 58, she died from breast cancer in [[West Orange, New Jersey]]. However, she believed that the true source of her illness later in life was related to the damaging pesticides that she had worked with for years.<ref name=":4">{{Cite book|title=The Union of Their Dreams: Power, Hope, and Struggle in Cesar Chavez's Farm Worker Movement|last=Pawel|first=Miriam|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|year=2010|isbn=978-1-60819-099-7|location=New York|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref>
{{Infobox person |name = Jessica Govea Thorbourne | birth_date = 1947 | birth_place = [[Porterville, California]] | death_date = January 23, 2005 | death_place = [[West Orange, New Jersey]] | death_cause = Breast Cancer | party = Democrat }}
== Early life == Govea Thorbourne was born in 1947 in [[Porterville, California]]<ref name=":6">{{Cite news|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/411667102?accountid=14868|title=Jessica Govea Thorbourne -- labor advocate|last=Hendricks|first=Tyche|date=March 8, 2005|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref> to Juan and Margaret Govea, who were [[migrant worker]]s.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/feb/02/local/me-thorbourne2|title=Jessica Govea Thorbourne, 58; Organizer for UFW Sounded Alarm on Pesticides|last=Woo|first=Elaine|date=February 2, 2005|website=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Los Angeles Times|access-date=November 3, 2016}}</ref> By the age of two, she had already began working in the fields.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilr.cornell.edu/news/remembering-legendary-organizer-jessica-govea-thorbourne|title=Remembering Legendary Organizer, Jessica Govea Thorbourne|last=Cornell University|first=|date=January 29, 2015|website=The ILR School Cornell University|publisher=Cornell University|access-date=}}</ref> At an early age, she began leading [[boycott]]s, such as her very successful [[Delano grape strike|grape boycott]] in Canada.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|title=Congressional Record Proceedins and Debates of the 109th Congress First Session Volume 151- Part 2|last=US Government Printing Office|first=|publisher=US Government Printing Office|year=2005|isbn=|location=Washington, District of Columbia|pages=2372|quote=|via=}}</ref> Govea Thorbourne graduated valedictorian from Bakersfield High School.<ref name=":2" /> She attended college for one year before deciding to join forces with [[Cesar Chavez]] in the [[United Farm Workers|United Farm Workers Union]].<ref name=":2" />
==Career == Govea Thorbourne began working with the United Farm Workers Union at the age of 19; however, she had been working with other migrant workers at the age of 2. Govea Thorbourne worked with the United Farm Workers and held many positions. Her most notable position was the national director of organizing. She then went on to become a labor educator at [[Rutgers University]] and [[Cornell University]]. While working for the union, she worked very closely with Cesar Chavez.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/92864029/B9D07BAE3EDD4D3DPQ/6?accountid=14868|title=Jessica G. Thorbourne, 58, Union Official|last=New York Times|first=|date=February 3, 2005|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref>
== Work with the United Farm Workers Union == Govea Thorbourne began working closely with Cesar Chavez for the United Farm Workers (UFW) at age 19, since her father was a Mexican-American community leader and worked closely with Chavez.<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/434148599?accountid=14868|title=Leader of Grape Boycott in Canada: Charismatic Organizer for Uniter Form Workers Union|last=Woo|first=Elaine|date=February 5, 2005|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref> At age 21, she led boycotts in Canada that led to UFW Union contracts with a California grape company.<ref name=":5" /> Additionally, she worked to raise awareness for Latino fieldworkers' exposure to dangerous pesticides.<ref name=":0" /> Govea Thorbourne later served as the national director of organizing for UFW.<ref name=":5" /> In 1977, she was elected a member of the UFW executive board.<ref name=":7">{{Cite book|title=Latinas in the United States: Set: A Historical Encyclopedia|last=Ruíz|first=Vicki L|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-253-34680-3|location=Indiana|pages=294–295|quote=|via=}}</ref>
