{{Infobox language |name=Kachama-Ganjule |states=[[Ethiopia]] |region=on islands in [[Lake Chamo]] and [[Lake Abaya]] |speakers={{sigfig|2830|2}} |ref=<ref>[http://www.csa.gov.et/index.php?option=com_rubberdoc&view=doc&id=264&format=raw&Itemid=521 Ethiopia 2007 Census] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114004942/http://www.csa.gov.et/index.php?option=com_rubberdoc&view=doc&id=264&format=raw&Itemid=521 |date=2010-11-14 }}</ref> |date=2007 census for Qechemigna |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Omotic languages|Omotic]] |fam3=[[North Omotic languages|North Omotic]] |fam4=[[Ometo languages|Ometo]] |fam5=North |iso3=kcx |glotto=kach1284 |glottorefname=Kachama-Ganjule |dia3=?Gidicho |dia1=Kachama |dia2=Ganjule }}
'''Kachama-Ganjule''' is an [[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic]] language spoken in [[Ethiopia]] on islands in [[Lake Chamo]] and [[Lake Abaya]]. Kachama is spoken on [[Gidicho island]] in Lake Abaya, whereas Ganjule was originally spoken on a small island in Lake Chamo. Now the Ganjule speakers have relocated to the west shore of the Lake. There still are about 1,000 monolinguals in this language.<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005. ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>
Blench (2006) lists Gidicho, Kachama, and Ganjule as separate languages. ''Ethnologue'' gives Gatame/Get'eme/Gats'ame as a synonym; however, Blench treats that as a separate languages as well, a synonym with Haruro/Harro. While he moves the others to the northern branch of the Ometo languages, he leaves Gatame/Haruro in the eastern branch.<ref>Blench, 2006. [http://rogerblench.info/Language/Afroasiatic/General/AALIST.pdf The Afro-Asiatic Languages: Classification and Reference List]</ref> No evidence is presented for treating these as separate languages.
