{{distinguish|Māori people|Mauri people}}

The '''Maouri''' people are an [[ethnic group]] in western [[Africa]]. They are one of the major ethnic groups of [[Niger]], and are concentrated around the ''Dallol Maouri'' (Maouri Valley) of the [[Niger River]], extending from [[Matankari]], near [[Niamey]], to [[Gaya, Niger|Gaya]]. They are a subgroup of the [[Hausa people]], and speak both the [[Hausa language]] and the [[Djerma language]] (or Zarma).<ref>{{cite journal | title=Le Territoire français Niger-Tchad | author=[[Société Belge d'Études Coloniales]] | journal=Bulletin de la Société belge d'études coloniales |date=September 1905 | volume=12 | pages=449–523}}</ref> When using the Zarma language, they are known as the Arawa people.<ref name="histdict"/>

The establishment of the Maouri people is uncertain, though many sources indicate descent from the [[Bornu Empire]]. The Maouri established two capitals in [[Matankari]] and [[Lougou]], with religious authority based in [[Bagaji]].<ref name="histdict">{{cite book | title=Historical Dictionary of Niger | publisher=Scarecrow Press | author=Idrissa, Abdourahmane and Samuel Decalo | year=2012 | pages=588 | isbn=0810870908 | edition=4th}}</ref>

The Maouri are [[animism|animistic]], with beliefs based on the [[Doguwa (religion)|Doguwa]] spirits.<ref name="histdict"/> [[Islam]] (especially in [[Dogondoutchi]]) and [[Christianity]] have since gained some adherents among the Maouri, but they still largely hold to traditional beliefs, including [[fetishes]].<ref name="histdict"/> They resisted an attempted forced [[religious conversion|conversion]] to Islam in the early 19th century during the [[Fulani jihad]]s and subsequent establishment of the [[Sokoto Caliphate]].<ref>{{cite book | title=The Rough Guide to West Africa | publisher=Penguin | author=Trillo, Richard | year=2008 | pages=1360 | isbn=1405380705}}</ref>

The Maouri were also subject to colonization by European powers. The Maouri lands were traded between the English and French colonies in West Africa under various treaties between 1890 and 1906.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Niger-Nigeria boundary, 1890-1906: a study of ethnic frontiers and a colonial boundary | publisher=Ohio University, Center for International Studies | author=Thom, Derrick J. | year=1975 | pages=42}}</ref> The French were particularly brutal in their administration of their colonies: in 1898 the priestess of Lougou, [[Sarraounia]], resisted an attack by the French [[Voulet-Chanoine Mission]] at the [[Battle of Lougou]]. The town ultimately fell, though Sarraounia's forces managed a retreat and were able to inflict ten casualties on the much more numerous and better-armed French soldiers.<ref name="histdict"/> The French later massacred the neighboring [[Konni (Hausa state)|Konni]] town of [[Birni-N'Konni]] in revenge.<ref>{{cite book | title=French Colonial Documentary: Mythologies of Humanitarianism | publisher=University of Minnesota Press | author=Bloom, Peter J. | year=2008 | pages=265 | isbn=0816646287}}</ref>

Today the Maouri are traders and farmers, and have a reputation as industrious people.<ref>{{cite book | title=Niger Foreign Policy and Government Guide, Volume 1 | publisher=International Business Publications | year=2011 | isbn=1433036878 | edition=6th | page=40}}</ref>

