__NOTOC__ The '''Tunjur''', or '''Tungur''', are a Sunni Muslim ethnic group found in eastern [[Chad]] and western [[Sudan]].<ref name="Appiah2005p241">{{cite book|author1=Anthony Appiah|author2=Henry Louis Gates, Jr.|title=Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TMZMAgAAQBAJ|year=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-517055-9|pages=241–242}}</ref>
The ethnic roots of the Tunjur people are unknown.<ref name="Appiah2005p241"/> According to their [[oral tradition]]s and some scholars, they are Arabs who migrated from the Arabian peninsula to Central Sudan either by way of North Africa and [[Tunis]] or by way of [[Nubia]]. In fact, as [[Nachtigal]] observed they resemble in features and behaviour the Arabs.<ref> Nachtigal/Fisher, ''Sahara'', II, 257/ III, 13.</ref> Other scholars suggest that they have non-Muslim Nilotic roots, that is from the River Nile region.<ref name="Appiah2005p241"/><ref name="Minahan2002p1130">{{cite book|author=James Minahan|title=Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: L-R |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u9Lq_8Ozf5cC |year=2002|publisher=Greenwood |isbn=978-0-313-32111-5|pages=1130–1131}}</ref>
They were a minority, but became the ruling class of Darfur and [[Ouaddai Empire|Wadai]] in the 13th century by peacefully taking over power from the [[Daju people|Daju]].<ref name="Appiah2005p241"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=J. D. Fage|author2=Roland Oliver|title=The Cambridge History of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GWjxR61xAe0C&pg=PA303|year=1975|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-20981-6|pages=303–304}}</ref> In 16th century, they were overthrown by an Arab group that founded the [[Keira dynasty]], and later merged with the [[Fur people]]. According to the local legends of the Fur people, Shau Dorshid, the last ruler of the Tunjur, was “driven out by his own people because he compelled his subjects to dig wells in the high rocky regions and to undertake the ardeous and useless task of levelling the Mail mountain peak, on the summit of which he wanted to establish his residence" <ref> Nachtigal/Fisher, ''Sahara'', III, 361/IV, 276.</ref> His capital is said to have been the site of [[Ain Farah]].{{cn|date=November 2016}}
About the middle of the 17th century, the Tunjur people were expelled from the Islamic Wadai empire by Abd-el-Kerim of the Maba people, and the Mabas controlled the slave supply caravans to the north.<ref name="Appiah2005p241"/><ref name="Minahan2002p1130"/> The Tunjur people then migrated west into their current location. Thereafter, they converted to Maliki [[fiqh]] of Sunni Islam.<ref name="Appiah2005p241"/>
==Society== They are farmers and live closely associated with the [[Fur people|Fur]]. Their own Tunjur language is now extinct, and they now speak [[Arabic]], Fur or Beri language as their first language.<ref name="Appiah2005p241"/>
==Contemporary issues== Like the Fur and the [[Zaghawa people|Zaghawa]], since the start of the [[Darfur conflict]] in February 2003, many Tunjur have been affected. A number of Tunjur have taken part in the fight against the Sudanese government, under the banners of the [[Sudan Liberation Movement]] (SLM). They are estimated around 176,000 people.{{cn|date=November 2016}}
